<setup>

    <math name="a"><selectFromSequence from="0" to="3" step="1"/></math>
    <math name="b"><selectFromSequence from="3" to="6" step="1" exclude="$a"/></math>
    <math name="c"><selectFromSequence from="-2" to="1" step="1" exclude="$a $b"/></math>
    <math name="d"><selectFromSequence from="2" to="5" step="1" exclude="$a $b $c"/></math>  
    <math name="d2" simplify>$d+1</math> 
    <math name="m"><selectFromSequence from="-2" to="-1" step="1"/></math>
    <math name="n"><selectFromSequence from="1" to="2" step="1"/></math>
    <math name="p"><selectFromSequence from="4" to="5" step="1"/></math>  

<math fixed name="x1">-3</math>
<math fixed name="x2"> 0</math>
<math fixed name="x3"> 3</math>
<math fixed name="x4"> 6</math>

</setup>

<p>
  The six open endpoints of the three line segments in the following graph can be dragged vertically.  Move the endpoints in order to construct the graph of a piecewise linear function <m>y = f(x)</m> with the following properties:
  <ul>
    <li>
      <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to -3^+} f(x) = $a</m>
    </li>  
    <li>
      <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 0^-} f(x) = $b;  \displaystyle \lim_{x \to 0^+} f(x) = $b</m>
    </li>  
    <li>
      <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 3^-} f(x) = $c</m>;  <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 3^+} f(x) = $d</m>
    </li>      
    <li>
      <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 6^-} f(x) = <math simplify>$d+1</math></m>
    </li>      
  </ul>
</p>

    <graph xmin="-3.5" xmax="7" ymin="-3" ymax="8" showNavigation="false" grid>
    
    
    <endpoint styleNumber="6" open name="p1" x="$x1" y="6">
      <constraints>
        <constrainToGrid dy="0.5"/>
      </constraints>
    </endpoint>
    
    <endpoint styleNumber="6" open name="p2" x="$x2" y="6">
      <constraints>
        <constrainToGrid dy="0.5"/>
      </constraints>
    </endpoint>
    
    <lineSegment name="Seg1" styleNumber="2" endpoints="$p1 $p2" />
        
    <endpoint styleNumber="6" open name="p3" x="$x2" y="7">
      <constraints>
        <constrainToGrid dy="0.5"/>
      </constraints>
    </endpoint>
    
    <endpoint styleNumber="6" open name="p4" x="$x3" y="7">
      <constraints>
        <constrainToGrid dy="0.5"/>
      </constraints>
    </endpoint>
    
    <lineSegment styleNumber="2" endpoints="$p3 $p4" />
    
    
    <endpoint styleNumber="6" open name="p5" x="$x3" y="6">
      <constraints>
        <constrainToGrid dy="0.5"/>
      </constraints>
    </endpoint>
    
    <endpoint styleNumber="6" open name="p6" x="$x4" y="6">
      <constraints>
        <constrainToGrid dy="0.5"/>
      </constraints>
    </endpoint>
    
    <lineSegment stylenumber="2" endpoints="$p5 $p6" />
    
  </graph>

<p> When your graph is ready, check your work: 
        <answer matchPartial>
          <award>
            <when><mathList>$p1.y $p2.y $p3.y $p4.y $p5.y $p6.y</mathList> = <mathList>$a $b $b $c $d $d2</mathList></when>
          </award> 
        </answer>  
</p>
  
<ol marker="a.">

  <li>
    <p>
      Complete the following sentence to explain why <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 3} f(x)</m> doesn't exist.  Since the left-hand limit <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 3^-} f(x) = </m><answer><award>$c</award></answer> and the right-hand limit <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 3^+} f(x) = </m><answer><award>$d</award></answer> and these two values are <answer><choiceInput inline> 
      <choice credit = "0">?</choice>
      <choice credit = "0">the same</choice>
      <choice credit = "1">different</choice>
    </choiceInput></answer>,
      the overall limit, <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 3} f(x)</m>, <answer><choiceInput inline> 
      <choice credit = "0">?</choice>
      <choice credit = "0">exists and equals $c</choice>
      <choice credit = "0">exists and equals $d</choice>
      <choice credit = "1">does not exist</choice>
    </choiceInput></answer>.
    </p>

  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
        List all values of <m>a</m> such that <m>-2.5 \lt a \lt 5.5</m> and for which <m>f'(a)</m> does not exist.  <mathInput name="notDiff"/>  
        <answer matchPartial>
          <award unorderedCompare>
            <when>$notDiff = <mathList>0 3</mathList></when>
          </award> 
        </answer> 
    </p>  

  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      For the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m> that you constructed, find the following derivative values:
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>f'($m) = </m><answer name="fPm">
          <award allowedErrorInNumbers="0.1" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><math simplify>($b-$a)/3</math></award></answer>
    </p>  
    <p>
      <m>f'($n) = </m><answer name="fPn">
          <award allowedErrorInNumbers="0.1" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><math simplify>($c-$b)/3</math></award></answer>
    </p>  
    <p>
      <m>f'($p) = </m><answer name="fPp">
          <award allowedErrorInNumbers="0.1" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><math simplify>($d2-$d)/3</math></award> </answer>
    </p>   
  
  <hint>
    <p>Remember that for a linear function, its slope is the same as the value of its derivative
    </p>
  </hint>
    
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      Which of the following statments is true?
      <answer>
        <choiceInput>
          <choice><m>f'(0)=<math simplify>($b-$a)/3</math></m></choice>
          <choice credit="1"><m>f'(0)</m> is undefined</choice>
          <choice><m>f'(0)=<math simplify>($c-$b)/3</math></m></choice>
    </choiceInput></answer>
    </p>
  </li>  
  
</ol>
